<p>

<b>Exalead</b> (pronounced  in English) is a French <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../023/4059023.xml">
search engine</link> involved in the <artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<engine wordnetid="103287733" confidence="0.8">
<motor wordnetid="103789946" confidence="0.8">
<device wordnetid="103183080" confidence="0.8">
<machine wordnetid="103699975" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../130/3645130.xml">
Quaero</link></machine>
</device>
</motor>
</engine>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
 project.</p>
<p>

Exalead provides thumbnail previews of the target pages along with the results, and allows advanced refining on the results page (language, geographic location, file type, categories) but also further data refinement, such as rich content (audio, video, RSS) and related terms, allowing users to browse the web by <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../006/27006.xml">
serendipity</link>.</p>

<sec>
<st>
 Exalead </st>

<p>

The company is a <link>
société anonyme</link> based in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../989/22989.xml">
Paris</link></site>
<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref> and founded in 2000 by <link>
François Bourdoncle</link>. Its name comes from the association between
<list>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../835/1835.xml">
prefix</link> <it>exa</it> which means 1018 (used as a generic term for size, to imply large coverage of pages)</entry>
<entry level="1" type="bullet">

 and the verb lead (as the customer is led through the search options)</entry>
</list>
</p>
<p>

Exalead tries to integrate research functions in one piece of software, combining <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../539/14539.xml">
Internet</link>, desktop and enterprise functionality.</p>
